## Test Anti-Pattern Audit — `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **Medium** | 2 |

This test class is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called, achieving high line coverage, but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is catastrophically broken (returning wrong values, corrupting data, silently no-op'ing).

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. Systemic Coverage Touching (class-wide pattern)

Every test follows the formula `call method → done` (or `→ Assert.IsNotNull`). The class exercises the full public surface area in declaration order with no meaningful assertions. This is the root cause of your "95% coverage, still has bugs" problem.

---

#### 2. No Assertion — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17-21)

Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was actually stored.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_StoresProduct()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored?.Price);
}
```

---

#### 3. Trivial `IsNotNull` — `GetProduct_Works` (line 25-29)

Only checks non-null. Would pass even if `GetProduct` returned a completely wrong product.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetProduct_ReturnsMatchingProduct()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));

    var result = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");

    Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", result?.Sku);
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", result?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, result?.Price);
}
```

---

#### 4. No Assertion — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32-36)

Never verifies the price was actually changed. A no-op `UpdatePrice` would pass.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_PersistsNewPrice()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));

    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

    var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
}
```

---

#### 5. No Assertion — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39-43)

Never verifies the product was actually deleted.

**Fix:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void RemoveProduct_MakesProductUnfindable()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));

